post_text:
Welcome Back! We are so excited to see your student’s faces again!

I just wanted to let parents of 3rd and 4th grade student know that we are continuing the breakfast snack program this year.

When your student arrives, have them tell the door monitor they are going to head to the cafeteria for a snack.

Currently we will be serving:
Tuesday & Thursday - whole grain single serve Poptarts or a whole grain muffin.
Wednesday & Friday - whole grain cereal bar or whole grain cereal bowl.
Each 45 cents

Everyday - carton 1% white & 1% chocolate milk, fresh fruit. Each 40 cents. Chilled water is also available for free with the purchase of an item.

One of each item may be taken. We will charge your student’s account for each item.

This service is not available on 11am dismissal days.

Expect a note to come home with your student.

post_text: Pauline Osman, Food Service Director, would like to thank everyone for their well wishes and wonderful comments as she soon steps into retirement. It has been such a privilege and personal joy to encourage our students over the years to try tasty and nutritious foods. The school cooks and district staff I have had the pleasure to work with have been dedicated professionals and care deeply about our students. Thank you. Best wishes to Mrs. Kendra Cooper as she takes over the reins of school nutrition for Williamsville-Sherman CUSD15.

post_text:
Thank you Williamsville Subway!

As we all know, Illinois has closed schools temporarily in an attempt to control the spread of COVID 19. In addition, restaurants are only able to operate for drive thru, curbside pickup, and delivery.

We believe this is the right decision, but also understand that it may present challenges to families in our community. We're here to help.

If you are concerned about ensuring your children have lunch, please call us and order a kids meal free of charge. Kids meals consist of a mini sub (turkey, ham, roast beef, or veggie) a side item, and 20oz. fountain drink.

Williamsville Subway # (217) 566-4324

We want to do our part to make sure our community gets through this.

#preparednotscared #nohungrykids

Valid at all Jacksonville, White Hall, Chatham & Williamsville Subways.

post_text:
Well, November started out with a partial power outage over lunch time at Sherman Elementary. A few 2nd grade students and all of the 3rd & 4th grade students were affected. Our large appliances stopped working, one of them being the ovens.

The students took it like a champ! No complaining! They had to choose between a WOWButter sandwich or a salad. The other items they were offered were; green beans, diced pears, cinnamon applesauce, fresh plums, coleslaw, baby carrots, celery sticks with WOWButter, string cheese stick, bread & butter and of course the favorite, fresh baked snickerdoodle cookie. Have a great weekend everyone!

post_text: This would be so beneficial for everyone involved.
shared_text:
Julie New Harbaugh
August 12, 2019 at 12:14 PM ·

PSA for all soon-to-be kindergarten mamas...
Practice eating “school lunch” with your kiddo. Make sure they can open everything you send with them. Talk about not eating off of the table in the lunchroom!!! Set a timer for 15 minutes and talk about how they may not finish eating and that’s ok. (This was HARD for little man.) Practice packing everything back up and talk about what is trash and what should come back home in their lunch box. Kindergarten lunch is a big adjustment and your child’s teacher will be super appreciative if you have prepared them for the experience!

post_text:
These last couple weeks of school are always both exciting and bittersweet. I wanted to take the opportunity to thank you all for letting us play a small role in your children's lives. Whether it's art, music, sports, etc - we enjoy seeing the kids discover who they are and what they love as the years go by. We may just be the "lunch ladies" but we want you, the parents, to know we care about the wellness of each and every student. For me, personally, it's always bittersweet to watch the 8th graders move forward. I'm sure the SES staff feels the same way about the 4th graders heading into middle school, as does the WHS staff as they watch the kids graduate.

Thank you all for a wonderful year. And to the ones moving on, keep doing great things! Your mountain is waiting. :)

-Amanda (speaking on behalf of all of us!)

post_text:
Here’s a recipe using apples to try this weekend. Only 10 minute prep time!

Caramel Apple Monkey Bread
1/2 C sugar
1 t ground cinnamon
2 (16.3z) cans refrigerated biscuits
1 1/2 small peeled & diced Granny Smith apples
1 C packed light brown sugar
3/4 C unsalted butter, melted

Oven 350. Grease bundt pan.
In medium bowl, combine sugar & cinnamon, set aside.
Separate dough, cut into 4th’s.
Toss all biscuits with sugar mixture.
Layer biscuits with diced apples in bundt pan.
Mix brown sugar & melted butter, pour evenly over the top of dough.
Bake 28-32 minutes, let cool 5 minutes before placing on serving plate and flipping upside down. Serve immediately.

You can find pictures and recipe at Justataste.com

post_text: The Sherman Elementary Kindergarten students will be celebrating The Great Apple Crunch this week! This collective Apple Crunch encourages and celebrates the use of healthy, Illinois-grown foods in cafeterias across the state. We Crunch to support our local farmers, to grow healthy eaters, and build strong communities across our state and region.
